description.plain:
Terror Jr is an American pop duo consisting of former The Cataracs member David “Campa” Singer-Vine and singer-songwriter Lisa Vitale. Founding member Felix Snow quietly left the group in early 2018.

The group debuted with the single “3 Strikes,” featured in Kylie Jenner’s “Glosses” short film. “Come First” became their biggest hit so far, peaking at number 10 on the Billboard Spotify Velocity chart. The trio released a project called Bop City on October 21, 2016 and a follow-up, Bop City 2: TerroRising on June 16, 2017. The series concluded with Bop 3: The Girl Who Cried Purple, released on September 29, 2017.

After almost 10 months of silence, Terror Jr returned in July 2018 with the first single from their debut album, “Heaven Wasn’t Made For Me.” Their long-anticipated debut album, Unfortunately, Terror Jr was released on January 25th, 2019.

After being dropped by their label (former member Felix Snow’s EFFESS imprint), they started self-releasing music in late 2019.

songs.title: 3 Strikes

description.plain:
3 Strikes is the premiere single from Terror Jr. The mysterious group made their first appearance early in the morning on March 31st by posting the song’s artwork to various social media platforms.

The track was later premiered in Kylie Jenner’s “Glosses” video, promoting her line of lip cosmetics, and then released on SoundCloud.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JtoRzI0vKJE

As it seems that Terror Jr just didn’t exist before the release of the video, it has been speculated that the artist is Kylie herself. According to Fader, Terror actually consists of lead singer Lisa, and Kiiara backers Felix Snow and Campa.

songs.title: Come First

description.plain: “Come First” is the fifth single released by mysterious pop trio Terror Jr. It’s a minimalistic song with a simple message about knowing your self worth and not taking that for granted.

songs.title: Sugar

description.plain: Sugar is about that one person you miss but don’t want to or can’t go back to. As they (sort of) explained in an email to The FADER, the song serves as an extension of their identity. “Terror Jr is a sunflower with a broken heart,” they wrote. “‘Sugar’ is that sunflower eating its own seeds and growing up again.”
